{"title_page": "Ida Wood", "text_new": "{{Hatnote|This article refers to the wealthy New York recluse; see [[Ida E. Woods]] for the astronomer with a similar name.}}\n\n'''Ida Mayfield Wood''' (1838 \u2013 March 12, 1932) was a noted American [[recluse]] and the third wife of politician and newspaper publisher and editor [[Benjamin Wood (American politician)|Benjamin Wood]] (1820\u20131900).\n\nShe moved to [[New York City]] in 1857 at the age of 19 and set her sights on 37-year-old Benjamin Wood, a married man.<ref name=SI>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/everything-was-fake-but-her-wealth-4621153/ |title=Everything Was Fake but Her Wealth |author=Karen Abbott |date=January 23, 2013 |magazine=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]]}}</ref> She boldly propositioned him in a letter dated May 28 and soon became his mistress; they had an illegitimate daughter, Emma Wood.<ref name=SI/> Ida claimed her father was Henry Mayfield, a Louisiana sugar planter.<ref name=SI/> After Wood's second wife died, they married in 1867.<ref name=SI/>\n\nHer husband was the publisher of the ''[[New York Daily News (19th century)|New York Daily News]]'', three-time member of [[United States Congress|Congress]] and two-time member of the [[New York State Senate]].<ref name=NYT/> As his wife, she gained entry into the elite level of New York society; she danced with the Prince of Wales in 1860 and met [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref name=SI/> Her brother-in-law was [[Fernando Wood]], twice mayor of New York City and three-time member of the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref name=NYT/>\n\nBenjamin was an inveterate gambler, however. He once even wagered the ''Daily News''; luckily he won.<ref name=SI/> Ida, on the other hand, was very careful with money. She got her husband to agree to split his winnings with her, while he was responsible for all of his losses.<ref name=SI/> By the time he died in 1900, she already had possession of essentially all of his wealth by this means.<ref name=SI/>\n\nShe herself edited and published the newspaper for a while, but then sold it in 1901 for more than $250,000<ref name=SI/> or around $300,000.<ref name=NYT>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/10/04/archives/mrs-woods-rubbish-pile-the-recluse-of-herald-square-by-joseph-a-cox.html |title=Mrs. Wood's Rubbish Pile; THE RECLUSE OF HERALD SQUARE. By Joseph A. Cox. 246 pp. New York: The Macmillan Company. $4.95. |date=October 4, 1964 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1907, she closed her bank account, taking out nearly $1 million.<ref name=SI/> Then Ida, her sister Mary E. Mayfield, and her daughter Emma took a two-room suite at the Herald Square Hotel, room 552, and became recluses. They had little contact with anyone, even hotel employees, for decades. Maids were not permitted inside to clean the rooms.\n\nEmma died in the hospital in 1928 at the age of 71. Then, when Mary became very ill, on May 5, 1931, Ida was finally forced to summon help.<ref name=SI/> This intrusion turned out badly for Ida. Mary died, and people became aware of the squalor in which Ida lived. They also discovered how rich she was. \n\nIn the midst of the [[Great Depression]], her relatives and their lawyers battled to gain control of her wealth.<ref name=NYT/> She was declared [[Competence (law)|incompetent]] in September 1931 and moved one floor down to two other rooms over her objections.<ref name=SI/> Many hundreds of thousands of dollars in cash and other valuables were found in her suite and in trunks stored in the hotel basement.<ref name=SI/> More than $3000 a month was spent on her care and protection.<ref name=NYT/> \n\nAfter she died on March 12, 1932, at the age of 93, no less than 1103 claimants squabbled over the distribution of her estate.<ref name=NYT/> The truth about her real past also emerged. She was actually born '''Ellen Walsh''', the daughter of poor Irish immigrant Thomas Walsh.<ref name=SI/> Her \"daughter\" Emma was actually her sister.<ref name=SI/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, Ida}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:19th-century American women]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hatnote|This article refers to the wealthy New York recluse; see [[Ida E. Woods]] for the astronomer with a similar name.}}\n\n'''Ida Mayfield Wood''' (1838 \u2013 March 12, 1932) was a noted American [[recluse]] and the third wife of politician and newspaper publisher and editor [[Benjamin Wood]] (1820\u20131900).\n\nShe moved to [[New York City]] in 1857 at the age of 19 and set her sights on 37-year-old Benjamin Wood, a married man.<ref name=SI>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/everything-was-fake-but-her-wealth-4621153/ |title=Everything Was Fake but Her Wealth |author=Karen Abbott |date=January 23, 2013 |magazine=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]]}}</ref> She boldly propositioned him in a letter dated May 28 and soon became his mistress; they had an illegitimate daughter, Emma Wood.<ref name=SI/> Ida claimed her father was Henry Mayfield, a Louisiana sugar planter.<ref name=SI/> After Wood's second wife died, they married in 1867.<ref name=SI/>\n\nHer husband was the publisher of the ''[[New York Daily News (19th century)|New York Daily News]]'', three-time member of [[United States Congress|Congress]] and two-time member of the [[New York State Senate]].<ref name=NYT/> As his wife, she gained entry into the elite level of New York society; she danced with the Prince of Wales in 1860 and met [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref name=SI/> Her brother-in-law was [[Fernando Wood]], twice mayor of New York City and three-time member of the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref name=NYT/>\n\nBenjamin was an inveterate gambler, however. He once even wagered the ''Daily News''; luckily he won.<ref name=SI/> Ida, on the other hand, was very careful with money. She got her husband to agree to split his winnings with her, while he was responsible for all of his losses.<ref name=SI/> By the time he died in 1900, she already had possession of essentially all of his wealth by this means.<ref name=SI/>\n\nShe herself edited and published the newspaper for a while, but then sold it in 1901 for more than $250,000<ref name=SI/> or around $300,000.<ref name=NYT>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/10/04/archives/mrs-woods-rubbish-pile-the-recluse-of-herald-square-by-joseph-a-cox.html |title=Mrs. Wood's Rubbish Pile; THE RECLUSE OF HERALD SQUARE. By Joseph A. Cox. 246 pp. New York: The Macmillan Company. $4.95. |date=October 4, 1964 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1907, she closed her bank account, taking out nearly $1 million.<ref name=SI/> Then Ida, her sister Mary E. Mayfield, and her daughter Emma took a two-room suite at the Herald Square Hotel, room 552, and became recluses. They had little contact with anyone, even hotel employees, for decades. Maids were not permitted inside to clean the rooms.\n\nEmma died in the hospital in 1928 at the age of 71. Then, when Mary became very ill, on May 5, 1931, Ida was finally forced to summon help.<ref name=SI/> This intrusion turned out badly for Ida. Mary died, and people became aware of the squalor in which Ida lived. They also discovered how rich she was. \n\nIn the midst of the [[Great Depression]], her relatives and their lawyers battled to gain control of her wealth.<ref name=NYT/> She was declared [[Competence (law)|incompetent]] in September 1931 and moved one floor down to two other rooms over her objections.<ref name=SI/> Many hundreds of thousands of dollars in cash and other valuables were found in her suite and in trunks stored in the hotel basement.<ref name=SI/> More than $3000 a month was spent on her care and protection.<ref name=NYT/> \n\nAfter she died on March 12, 1932, at the age of 93, no less than 1103 claimants squabbled over the distribution of her estate.<ref name=NYT/> The truth about her real past also emerged. She was actually born '''Ellen Walsh''', the daughter of poor Irish immigrant Thomas Walsh.<ref name=SI/> Her \"daughter\" Emma was actually her sister.<ref name=SI/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, Ida}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:19th-century American women]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Benjamin Wood", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ida_Wood"}
